# dnd_mud data layer

## YAML conventions

- Game data lives in `database/` — races, classes, equipment, strings, etc.
- User-facing text in `database/strings/{ru,en}.yaml` with matching keys
- Entity names often bilingual: `name: { ru: "...", en: "..." }`
- Do not hardcode game data in Python — add or extend YAML files

## Mods (`mods/`)

```yaml
name: "Mod title"
version: "1.0"
type: "addon"    # addon | mod
files:
  - target: "database/races/races.yaml"
    action: "append"   # append | replace | delete
    data: [...]
```

State tracked in `database/content/mods_state.yaml` via `core/mod_loader.py`.

## Adventures (`adventures_scripts/`)

Scenario YAML referenced from `database/content/adventures.yaml`.
Keep narrative and mechanics data in YAML, not in UI code.

## When editing data

1. Keep `ru` and `en` in sync for new keys
2. Follow existing file structure under `database/`
3. Run `make test` after data changes that affect loading
